Talking heads forget what got valuations here... low interest rates. Higher interest rates compress valuations.

Why is the recent rate rise dangerous? Because, when assessing the impact of a rate rise we should observe debt service as a product of two independent variables: the amount of debt and the interest rate imposed on that debt. @tomkeene @jimcramer
smart and rigorous in his analysis

There is a remarkable lack of accountability in the business news platforms. I just listened to the self confident bullish spiel of someone that gave an equally convicted bearish spiel at the February bottom.

I will no longer comment on the lack of transparency/accountability of media in the future - its so bad that commentators dont even remember what they said weeks ago. Selective disclosure is not permitted by regulatory authorities. And I have no interest in policing them anymore.

Memo to everyone that thinks the recent interest rate rise is inconsequential - from an historical prospect. That is wrong given the mountain load of record private and public debt outstanding compared to any time in history. @tomkeene @jimcramer @CNBCFastMoney
and too many bulls get excited ...about eight straight up days
Market participants (bond vigilantes) impact daily movement in interest rates. @ScottWapnerCNBC @CNBCFastMoney
@ScottWapnerCNBC should ask @CNBCFastMoney panelists about the record level of private and public debt - and the rising rate impact/ramifications.

I admire the certainty and the self confidence of the media's talking heads. I wish was as confident in view. But with so many potential political, geopolitical, economic and market outcomes (many of them adverse) - I cant share their certainty of view.
